fields.explanation: This particle is used to show that something owns something else. The object to the left of the の particle is the one that owns the object to the right of the particle. If we said AのB, then this would mean A's B. For example, トミーのハンカチ would mean "Tommy's hankierchief". You can think of it as having a similar use to "'s" in English. This can also be used in between multiple nouns to indicate possession. For example, 私の右の目。 私の右 alone translates to "my right" and you can add another の particle in front of it and a noun such as 目 to say "my right eye".
fields.name: の
fields.structure: A の B, A の B の C の D etc...

fields.explanation: You can use this with two nouns to mean "and". Can also use it in between multiple nouns so say A and B and C.
fields.name: と

fields.explanation: This connects two nouns into one. For example, イタリアのレストラン (Italian Restaruant) is two separate nouns but turned into one noun. more nouns into one by connecting it with another の. This is technically the same as the の particle for possession, but just another usecase. Instead of being like an "'s", you can think of it as meaning "of". So イタリアのレストラン = The restaurant of Italy = The Italian restaurant.
fields.name: の
fields.structure: A の B, A の B の C の D etc...

fields.explanation: これ is a pronoun meaning "this" and is used to refer to something that is relatively close to the speaker. It is used when talking about an object, idea, or situation that is close to the speaker. For example if, Person A was talking to someone about his shoes, the game he is playing, the food he is eating etc. he would refer to it with これ. This applies to distance as well, if there is something in close to you that you are talking about, you would use これ.
fields.name: これ

fields.explanation: それ is a pronoun meaning "that" and is used to refer to something that is relatively far from the speaker but close to the listener. It is used when talking about an object, idea, or situation that the listener is aware of. For example if, Person A was talking to Person B about Person B's shoes, the game Person B is playing, the food Person B is eating etc. he would refer to it with それ. This applies to distance as well, if there is something not close to you but close to the person you you are talking to, you would use それ.
fields.name: それ

fields.explanation: あれ is a pronoun meaning "that" and is used to refer to something that is far from both the speaker and the listener. It is used when talking about an object, idea, or situation that neither the speaker nor the listener is close to, but both are aware of. For example if, Person A and Person B see a stranger and are talking about the stranger's shoes, the game the stranger is playing, the food the stranger is eating etc. he would refer to it with あれ. This applies to distance as well, if there is something far from you and the person you are talking to, you would use あれ.
fields.name: あれ

fields.translation_text: The slippers are cute? The white skirt is also cute. Haruko-chan is cute today.

fields.explanation: ちゃん is an informal and affectionate honorific, usually used for close friends, children, or pets.
さん is a more formal and respectful honorific, used when addressing someone you are not close to or someone of higher status.
The 'は' particle is being used to mark the object スリッパ as the topic so we know that Naruhaya is referring to the slippers when she says cute.

This is translated as "you" because it is more natural in English but in Japanese, the word "you" is not used with friends, saying the name is the standard.
